Fluctuating Temporal Trends:

Median growth_rate hovers near 0% (2018–2024), peaking slightly in 2020 (5.85%) and 2023 (3.70%). Mean growth spikes in 2023 (1479.85%, SD = 9652.40%) , with 2022 (977.92%) and 2021 (376.23%) also high. Recovery rates (positive growth) are highest in 2020 (54%) and lowest in 2024 (29%). No consistent linear trend; 2023 shows the highest volatility.

Assembly Disparities: Tamale leads with the highest mean growth (2047.67%, processed mean = 295.02%), but median growth is modest (9.2%). WA (mean = 334.57%, processed = 161.88%) and Yendi (mean = 187.35%, processed = 152.67%) follow, with spikes like WA’s Property Rates (2418.6%, 2023). Bolgatanga (mean = 16.26%) and East Mamprusi (mean = 24.98%) have the lowest growth, with medians at 0%. Volatility is highest in WA (5.60) and Yendi (5.67).

Revenue Item Performance: Other Rates (mean = 1693.70%, processed = 217.23%) and Fines (mean = 1081.92%, processed = 186.35%) show the highest growth. Fees (mean = 413.10%, processed = 182.84%) and Investment (mean = 199.73%) also have high spikes. Licences (mean = 29.14%, median = 14.35%) and Land (incl Miscellaneous) (mean = 53.65%) are more stable but lower. Property Rates (mean = 108.89%, median = 0%) has notable peaks . Rent is moderate (mean = 75.59%). Extreme negatives (≤-50%) are most frequent in Land (8 cases); extreme positives (≥100%) in Other Rates and Fees (8 and 7 cases). Licences are the most stable (stability = -0.42).

High Variability : Box plots show Tamale and WA with the widest ranges, while Bolgatanga and East Mamprusi are tighter.

Growth Categories: Processed data categorizes growth: 50% of observations are “Stable” (≤0%), 25% in “Moderate Decline” (-20% to 0%), and ~12.5% in “Moderate Growth” (0% to 20%). “Hyper Growth” (>100%) is rare but significant in Tamale (Other Rates) and WA (Property Rates). “Collapse” (<-50%) occurs in ~5% of cases, mostly Land and Other Rates.

Box Plots: Tamale and WA have outliers; Bolgatanga is most consistent. Fines and Other Rates show variability.

  • Observations from the analysis

The growth_rate distribution is right-skewed (skewness = 12.7, kurtosis = 172.73), with a median of 0% and a mean of 454.03% driven by outliers ( Other Rates at 66,911.2% in Tamale, 2023; Fines at 43,990%). Half of the observations (50%) are at or below 0% (1st quartile = -12.97%, min = -100%). Weighted summaries (excluding >1000%) show more stable means (37.0% in 2023, -1.84% in 2024).

Stable Median Trends with Sporadic Peaks:

Median growth_rate is near 0% for 2018, 2019, 2022, and 2024, peaking at 5.85% in 2020 and 3.7% in 2023, with a dip to 0.55% in 2021. Mean growth is highest in 2023 (1479.85%, SD = 9652.40%), followed by 2022 (977.92%) and 2021 (376.23%). Positive growth ratios peak in 2020 (54.2%) and drop to 26.1% in 2024. Line plots and heatmaps highlight 2023 as a high-growth year (WA’s Property Rates at 2418.6%) and 2024 as a decline.

Assembly Disparities:

Tamale leads with a mean growth_rate of 2047.67% (median = 9.2%). WA (mean = 334.57%, median = 0%) and Yendi (mean = 187.35%, median = 0%) follow, with WA’s 2023 Property Rates spike notable. West Gonja (mean = 97.72%), East Mamprusi (mean = 24.98%), and Bolgatanga (mean = 16.26%) have lower growth (medians = 0%). High variability ( Tamale’s SD = 10,602.30%) is evident in box plots, but the Kruskal-Wallis test (χ² = 3.632, p = 0.604) finds no significant differences, likely due to some elese.

Revenue Item Performance with Reliable Leaders:

Other Rates (mean = 1693.70%, median = 0%) and Fines (mean = 1081.92%, median = 0%) have high means. Fees (mean = 413.10%, median = 13.90%) and Licences (mean = 29.14%, median = 14.35%) show consistent positive medians, indicating reliability. Investment (mean = 199.73%), Property Rates (mean = 108.89%), Rent (mean = 75.59%), and Land (incl Miscellaneous) (mean = 53.65%) have lower medians (0–6.4%). The Kruskal-Wallis test (χ² = 11.097, p = 0.134) finds no significant differences, but faceted plots confirm Fees/Licences’ stability and Property Rates’ 2023 peak.

Dynamic Growth States:

Alluvial plots show “Stagnant” (0%) as the dominant state ( 21 cases in 2018), followed by “Moderate Growth” (0–50%) and “Decline” (<0%). “Hyper Growth” (>50%) peaks in 2019 (10 cases) and 2023 ( Tamale-Other Rates, WA-Property Rates), while “Collapse” (<-50%) is rare ( 5 cases in 2019). Heatmaps highlight Tamale (2020, 2023) and WA (2023) as growth leaders, with Bolgatanga and East Mamprusi stagnant.

Faceted Line Plots: Property Rates (WA, 2023) and Other Rates (Tamale, 2023) show sharp spikes; Fees and Licences have smooth, positive trends. Bolgatanga and East Mamprusi are flat.

Faceted Box Plots: Tamale and WA have wide ranges for Fines, Other Rates, and Fees; Licences and Land are stable.

Heatmaps: Tamale (2020, 2023) and WA (2023) show positive medians; Fees and Licences are consistently positive. Investment and Bolgatanga stagnate.

Statistical Challenges: Non-significant Kruskal-Wallis results (p = 0.604 for assemblies, p = 0.134 for items) suggest outliers and skewness obscure group differences. Median-based analyses (Tamale’s 9.2% vs. Bolgatanga’s 0%, Fees’ 13.90% vs. Fines’ 0%) and visualizations indicate some disparities.

  • Summary of Trends and Patterns

Temporal: Revenue growth is generally stagnant (median ~0%), with a significant 2023 peak and a 2024 decline, reflecting unchnages rather than sustained growth.

Assemblies: Tamale and WA lead with volatile, high-growth potential ( 2023 spikes), while Bolgatanga and East Mamprusi remain stagnant, indicating regional disparities.

Revenue Items: Fees and Licences are reliable, consistent performers, while Other Rates, Fines, and Property Rates are volatile with high-reward potential ( 2023).

Conclusion

The rev_growth dataset reveals a volatile revenue landscape for Ghana’s assemblies from 2018 to 2024, characterized by a median growth_rate near 0% and hyper-growth spikes (up to 66,911.2%) in 2023, driven by Other Rates and Fines in Tamale, and Property Rates in WA. Fees and Licences emerge as reliable revenue sources with consistent positive growth (medians 13.90–14.35%), while Bolgatanga and East Mamprusi remain stagnant (medians = 0%). The 2020–2021 COVID period shows low medians but high variability, with a strong recovery in 2023 followed by a decline in 2024 (median = 0%, mean = -1.84%). Extreme outliers and skewness obscure statistical significance (Kruskal-Wallis p > 0.05), but visualizations and medians highlight clear performance gaps.

Implications or policy Recommendations:

Budget Planning: Anticipate low growth in 2025 based on 2024’s decline (median = 0%, mean = -1.84%). Prioritize stable Fees and Licences for revenue reliability.

Strengthen Stable Revenue Streams: Enhance collection and enforcement of Fees and Licences to ensure consistent revenue, leveraging their stability across assemblies.

Replicate 2023 Successes: Investigate drivers of 2023 hyper-growth ( WA’s Property Rates, Tamale’s Other Rates), such as policy reforms or economic factors, to replicate in other assemblies and years.

Address Regional Stagnation: Implement targeted interventions in Bolgatanga and East Mamprusi, focusing on high-potential items like Fees, to boost growth.

Verify extreme values ( 66,911.2%) for data accuracy as they skew analysas.

Prepare for 2024 Decline: Develop contingency budgets for 2025, anticipating continued low growth based on 2024’s negative trends.

The skewness (skewness = 12.7) necessitates median-based to uncover group differences missed by Kruskal-Wallis tests.
